  <section id="forms">
    <h>forms</h>
    <p>Like all proper nouns, anthroponymic proper nouns have - <ul>
        <li>gender – every anthroponymic proper noun is either feminine or masculine – <ul>
            <li><g>Ealasaid</g>
              <en>Elizabeth</en> and <g>Raonaid</g>
              <en>Rachel</en> are feminine anthroponymic proper nouns</li>
            <li><g>Iain</g>
              <en>John</en> and <g>Dòmhnall</g>
              <en>Donald</en> are masculine anthroponymic proper nouns</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>case – every anthroponymic proper noun is either nominative or dative or genitive or vocative – <ul>
            <li>The genitive and dative forms of the feminine proper noun <g>Mairead</g>
              <en>Margaret</en> are both <g>Maireid</g>; the vocative form is <g>Mhairead</g>.</li>
            <li>The genitive and vocative forms of the masculine proper noun <g>Seòras</g>
              <en>George</en> are both <g>Sheòrais</g>; the nominative and dative forms are just
                <g>Seòras</g>.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <p>As with other proper nouns, the dative and genitive forms of a feminine anthroponymic proper
      noun are created by slenderising the corresponding nominative form (<g>Mairead</g> ⇒
          <g>Maire<emph>id</emph></g><!--<ed>Never Maireide?</ed>-->), and the genitive form of a masculine anthroponymic proper
      noun is created by both slenderising and leniting the corresponding nominative form
        (<g>Tormod</g>
      <en>Norman</en> ⇒ <g>Thormo<emph>id</emph></g>).</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h>dependencies</h>
    <section id="modifiers">
      <h>modifiers</h>
      <p>Like other proper nouns, an anthroponymic proper noun can have one or more (post-)modifiers
        – <ul>
          <li>adjectives – <g>Iain <emph>bochd</emph></g>
            <en>poor John</en>, <g>Mairead <emph>bhàn</emph>
              <emph>bhòidheach</emph></g>
            <en>pretty fair Margaret</en></li>
          <li>prepositions – <g>Dòmhnall <emph>à</emph> Lunnainn</g>
            <en>Donald from London</en></li>
          <li>relative clauses – <g>Tòmas <emph>a bha</emph> anns an sgoil còmhla rium</g>
            <en>Thomas who was at school with me</en>, <g>Raonaid nach ith feòil</g>
            <en>Rachel who doesn’t eat meat</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <!--
      <p><ed>Can a genitive common noun be used to modify an anthroponymic proper noun?</ed></p>
      <p><ed>Add recap of rules for leniting and slenderising adjectives?</ed></p> -->
      <section>
        <h>nicknames</h>
        <p>Adjective modifiers are frequently used in nicknames – <ul>
            <li><g>Mairead Bhàn</g>
              <en>Fair Margaret</en>
              <ul>
                <li>dative – le <g>Maireid Bhàin</g> (<emph>alt.</emph> le Mairead Bhàn)</li>
                <li>genitive – taigh <g>Maireid Bhàin</g></li>
              </ul></li>
            <li><g>Seumas Mòr</g>
              <en>Big James</en><ul>
                <li>dative – le <g>Seumas Mòr</g></li>
                <li>genitive – taigh <g>Sheumais Mhòir</g></li>
              </ul></li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <p>Examples from modern usage – <xl id="mod-adj--other">
            <li>
              <gd>’Se an aon duine a bha coltach ris anns a’ bhaile <m>Tormod Beag</m> a bhiodh a’
                fuireach anns an tigh fad na tìde ’s a bhiodh ag òl gun sgur.</gd>
              <tr>The only man who was like him in the town was Little Norman who stayed at home all
                the time and drank non-stop.</tr>
              <ref text="198">td. 4</ref>
            </li>
            <li>
              <gd>Làrna-mhàireach thachair Cairstìona rium ’s i dol a thadhal air bean <m>Mhurchaidh
                  Mhóir</m>.</gd>
              <tr>The next day I bumped into Christine as she was going to visit Big Murdo’s
                wife.</tr>
              <ref text="198">td. 7</ref>
            </li>
          </xl>
        </p>
      </section>
      <section>
        <h>non-patronymic surnames</h>
        <p>‘Non-patronymic’ surnames are a special kind of adjective post-modifier of an
          anthroponymic proper noun, with the same patterns of lenition and slenderisation – <ul>
            <li><g>Mairead Chaimbeul</g>
              <en>Margaret Campbell</en>
              <ul>
                <li>dative – le <g>Mairead Chaimbeul</g></li>
                <li>genitive – taigh <g>Maireid Chaimbeil</g></li> <!-- taigh Maireid Caimbeile??-->
              </ul></li>
            <li><g>Tormod Dòmhnallach</g>
              <en>Norman Donaldson</en>
              <ul>
                <li>dative – le <g>Tormod Dòmhnallach</g></li>
                <li>genitive – taigh <g>Thormoid Dhòmhnallaich</g></li>
              </ul></li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <p>cf. <g>Camshron</g>
          <en>Cameron</en>, <g>Friseal</g>
          <en>Fraser</en>.</p>
        <!-- <p>Include examples from Cox?</p> -->
      </section>
    </section>

    <section id="specifier">
      <h>specifier</h>
      <p>Like other proper nouns, an anthroponymic proper noun can have a (post-)specifier – <ul>
          <li>genitive proper noun – <ul>
              <li><g>Mairead <emph>Sheumais</emph></g>
                <en>James’ Mary; Mary the wife/daughter of James</en>
                <ul>
                  <li>dative – le <g>Mairead Sheumais</g></li>
                  <li>genitive – taigh <g>Maireid<!--(e?)--> Sheumais</g>
                    <!-- <ed>Is this acceptable?</ed> --></li>
                </ul></li>
              <li><g>Dòmhnall Chanaidh</g>
                <en>Donald of Canna</en>
                <ul>
                  <li>dative – le <g>Dòmhnall Chanaidh</g></li>
                  <li>genitive – taigh <g>Dhòmhaill Chanaidh</g>
                    <!-- <ed>Is this acceptable?</ed> --></li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>pre-specified common noun –<ul>
              <li><g>Dòmhnall a’ <emph>Mhinisteir</emph></g>
                <en>the Minister’s Donald; Donald the son of the Minister</en>
                <ul>
                  <li>dative – le <g>Dòmhnall a’ Mhinisteir</g></li>
                  <li>genitive – taigh <g>Dhòmhnaill a’ Mhinisteir</g>
                    <!-- <ed>Is this acceptable?</ed> --></li>
                </ul></li>
              <li><g>Seòras a’ <emph>Ghearasdain</emph></g>
                <en>George of Fort William</en>
                <ul>
                  <li>dative – le <g>Seòras a’ Ghearasdain</g></li>
                  <li>genitive – taigh <g>Sheòrais a’ Ghearasdain</g>
                    <!-- <ed>Is this acceptable?</ed> --></li>
                </ul></li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>post-specified common noun – <ul>
              <li><g>Seonag <emph>Ministeir</emph> na h-Eaglaise</g>
                <en>Janie the wife/daughter of the Church Minister</en>
                <!-- <ed>Is this grammatical?</ed> -->
                <ul>
                  <li>dative – le <g>Seonag Ministeir na h-Eaglaise</g></li>
                  <li>genitive – taigh <g>Seonaig Ministeir na h-Eaglaise</g>
                    <!-- <ed>Is this acceptable?</ed> --></li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>


      <p>The specifier can refer to a close relative (parent or spouse) by name or by profession, or
        a place of residence or origin.</p>
      <p>Other examples –<ul>
          <li><g>Sìleas na Ceapaich</g>
            <en>Cicely of Keppoch</en>
            <!--<ul>
              <li>dative – le <g>Sìleas na Ceapaich</g></li>
              <li>genitive – taigh <g>Sìleis na Ceapaich</g>
                <ed>Is this acceptable?</ed></li>
            </ul>-->
          </li>
          <li><g>Màiri Mhòr nan Òran</g>
            <en>lit. Big Mary of the Songs</en>
            <!--<ul>
              <li>dative – le <g>Màiri Mhòr nan Òran</g></li>
              <li>genitive – taigh <g>Màiri Mhòir nan Òran</g>
                <ed>Is this acceptable?</ed></li>
            </ul>-->
          </li>
        </ul></p>

      <section>
        <h>chained patronymics</h>
        <p>Specified anthroponymic proper nouns can be ‘chained’ to form embedded patronymics – <ul>
            <li><g>Iain Dhòmhnaill Sheumais Dhonnchaidh</g>
              <en>John of Donald of James of Duncan</en></li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <p>Unlike with common nouns, a proper noun which is the (post-)specifier of another noun is
          genitive, even if it has a specifier itself, cf. <bad>Iain Dòmhnall Seumas
            Dhonnchaidh</bad>.</p>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section id="apposition">
      <h>apposition</h>
      <p>Like other proper nouns, an anthroponymic proper noun can stand in apposition to a
        specified common noun, with the second noun being in the nominative case regardless of the
        case of the first noun – <ul>
          <li><g>Dòmhnall an sagart</g>
            <en>Donald the priest</en>
            <ul>
              <li>dative – le <g>Dòmhnall an t-sagart</g></li>
              <li>genitive – taigh <g>Dhòmhnaill an t-sagart</g></li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><g>Mairead bean a’ Mhinisteir</g>
            <en>Margaret the minister’s wife</en>
            <ul>
              <li>dative – le <g>Mairead bean a’ Mhinisteir</g></li>
              <li>genitive – taigh <g>Maireid bean a’ Mhinisteir</g></li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>

      <section>
        <h>patronymics and patronymic surnames</h>
        <p>Using apposition, a second kind of patronymic can be formed – <ul>
            <li><g>Mairead nighean Thormoid</g>
              <en>Margaret, daughter of Norman</en>
              <ul>
                <li>dative – le <g>Mairead nighean Thormoid</g></li>
                <li>genitive – taigh <g>Maireid nighean Thormoid</g></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li><g>Dòmhnall mac Dhòmhnaill mhic Sheumais mhic Dhonnchaidh</g>
              <en>Donald, son of Donald, son of James, son of Duncan</en>
              <!--<ed>Why mhic and not mic?</ed>-->
              <ul>
                <li>dative – le <g>Dòmhnall mac Dhòmhnaill mhic Sheumais mhic Dhonnchaidh</g></li>
                <li>genitive – taigh <g>Dhòmhnaill mhic Dhòmhnaill mhic Sheumais mhic
                  Dhonnchaidh</g></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <p>Apposition also forms the basis for ‘patronymic’ surnames – <ul>
            <li><g>Mairead NicNèill</g>
              <en>Margaret MacNeil</en>
              <ul>
                <li>dative – le <g>Mairead NicNèill</g></li>
                <li>genitive – taigh <g>Maireid NicNèill</g></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li><g>Seumas MacDhòmhnaill</g>
              <en>James MacDonald</en>
              <ul>
                <li>dative – le <g>Seumas MacDhòmhnaill</g></li>
                <li>genitive – taigh <g>Sheumais MhicDhòmhnaill</g></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h>double-barrelled given names</h>
        <p>Apposition is the basis for ‘double-barrelled’ given names – <ul>
            <li><g>Sìleas Mairead</g>
              <en>Julia Margaret</en>
              <ul>
                <li>dative – le <g>Sìleas Mairead</g></li>
                <li>genitive – taigh <g>Sìleis Maireid</g></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li><g>Dòmhnall Seumas</g>
              <en>Donald James</en>
              <ul>
                <li>dative – le <g>Dòmhnall Seumas</g></li>
                <li>genitive – taigh <g>Dhòmhnaill Sheumais</g></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <p>Examples from modern usage – <xl id="double-barrel-other">
            <li>
              <gd>“Tha feadhainn ag ràdh gu bheil <m>Tormod Iain</m> a’ bualadh a mhnatha.”</gd>
              <tr>“People are saying that Norman John hits his wife.”</tr>
              <ref text="198">td.6.</ref>
            </li>
          </xl>
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h>titles</h>
        <p>Apposition is the basis for titles and honorifics – <ul>
            <li><g>An t-Ollamh Dòmhnall (MacDhòmhnaill)</g>
              <en>Doctor/Professor Donald (MacDonald)</en>
              <ul>
                <li>dative – leis <g>an Ollamh Dòmhnall (MacDhòmhnaill)</g></li>
                <li>genitive – taigh <g>an Ollaimh Dòmhnall (MacDhòmhnaill)</g></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <p>Basic examples from Cox (2017: 129) – <g>A’ Bhanrigh Bhioctòria</g>
          <en>Queen Victoria</en>, <g>An (Dàrna) Rìgh Seumas</g>
          <en>King James (the Second)</en>, <g>A’ Bhana-phrionnsa Anna</g>
          <en>Princess Anne</en>, <g>Am Prionnsa Teàrlach</g>
          <en>Prince Charles</en>, <g>A’ Mhaighdean Eilidh Ghreumach</g>
          <en>Miss Helen Graham</en>. <g>A’ Bhean-uasal Oighrig NicDhòmhnaill</g>
          <en>Lady Euphemia MacDonald</en>, <g>An t-Urramach Ailean Friseal</g>
          <en>Reverend Alan Fraser</en>.</p>
        <p>Examples from Cox (2017: 129) with no anthroponymic proper noun – <g>An Sagart
            MacLeòid</g>
          <en>Priest? MacLeod</en>, <g>Am Ministear NicAsgail</g>
          <en>Minister? MacAskill</en>, <g>A’ Bhean-phòsta NicDhonnchaidh</g>
          <en>Mrs Donaldson</en>, <g>An t-Athair MacFhionghain</g>
          <en>Father MacKinnon</en>.</p>


