  <section id="lenition">
    <h>lenition</h>
    <section>
      <h>masculine</h>
      <p>A masculine anthroponymic proper noun which is the (genitive) (post-)specifier of another
        noun is generally lenited – <ul>
          <li><g>taigh Dhòmhnaill</g>
            <en>Donald’s house</en><!--, cf. <bad>taigh Dòmhna(i)ll</bad>--></li>
          <li><g>cù Mhurchaidh</g> – <en>Murdo’s dog</en><!--, cf. <bad>cù Murcha(i)dh</bad>--></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>However, in traditional (especially formal) usage, lenition may be ‘blocked’ if adjacent
        consonants are both dental or even both velar – <ul>
          <li><g>Cla<emph>nn D</emph>òmhnaill</g>
            <en>Clan Donald</en></li>
          <li><g>Cla<emph>nn D</emph>onnchaidh</g>
            <en>Clan Duncan</en></li>
          <li><g>ma<emph>c C</emph>aluim</g>
            <en>Calum’s son</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>In addition, lenition is optional with English-derived masculine anthroponymic proper nouns
        – <ul>
          <li><g>màthair B[h]ob</g>
            <en>Bob’s mother</en></li>
          <li><g>taigh M[h]urdo</g>
            <en>Murdo’s house</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h>feminine</h>
      <p>A feminine anthroponymic proper noun which is the (genitive) (post-)specifier of another
        noun is traditionally not lenited – <ul>
          <li><g>taigh Màiri</g>
            <en>Mary’s house</en></li>
          <li><g>cù Flòraidh</g> – <en>Flora’s dog</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>However, it is common nowadays in some dialects (e.g. Skye) to see/hear feminine anthroponymic proper nouns lenited in
        these contexts – <ul>
          <li><g>taigh Mhàiri</g></li>
          <li><g>cù Fhlòraidh</g></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>This goes also for those borrowed from English – <ul>
          <li><g>each P[h]eigi</g>
            <en>Peggy’s horse</en></li>
          <li><g>gillean B[h]essie</g>
            <en>Bessie’s boys</en></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </section>
